'''Broadcast Exchange Format''' ('''BXF''') is an [[SMPTE]] standard for data exchange in the broadcasting industry.
==History== BXF was developed to replace various archaic types of exchange for playlists, record lists and other data in broadcasting. Version 1.0 (SMPTE standard 2021) was published in 2008. Over 150 SMPTE members have been involved in defining the standard. BXF is [[XML]] based.<ref>[http://broadcastengineering.com/automation/bxf-explained BXF explained | Automation content from Broadcast Engineering]</ref>
[[Myers Information Systems]] was the first to use BXF, in partnership with [[Crispin Corporation]].<ref>George Winslow, "Navigating the New Traffic," ''Broadcasting & Cable'', October 18, 2010.</ref>
== See also == * AAF, [[Advanced Authoring Format]] * [[Broadcast Wave Format|BWF]], broadcast Wave Format * [[Material Exchange Format|MXF]], Material eXchange Format
